      <section id="fs-id1596051" class="section-summary">
<title>Summary</title>
<list id="fs-id2446096"><item id="import-auto-id1586681">Newton’s laws of motion can be applied in numerous situations to solve problems of motion.</item>
      <item id="import-auto-id1586684">Some problems will contain multiple force vectors acting in different directions on an object. Be sure to draw diagrams, resolve all force vectors into horizontal and vertical components, and draw a free-body diagram. Always analyze the direction in which an object accelerates so that you can determine whether <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>F</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>net</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>ma</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> or <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>F</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>net</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> .</item>
      <item id="import-auto-id3305501">The normal force on an object is not always equal in magnitude to the weight of the object. If an object is accelerating, the normal force will be less than or greater than the weight of the object. Also, if the object is on an inclined plane, the normal force will always be less than the full weight of the object.</item>
      <item id="import-auto-id2653368">Some problems will contain various physical quantities, such as forces, acceleration, velocity, or position. You can apply concepts from kinematics and dynamics in order to solve these problems of motion.</item>
      </list></section>

