      </exercise><exercise id="fs-id2441621" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1446886">
        <para id="import-auto-id3033810"><title>Integrated Concepts</title> A large rocket has a mass of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>6</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> kg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> at takeoff, and its engines produce a thrust of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>50</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>7</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> N</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>. (a) Find its initial acceleration if it takes off vertically. (b) How long does it take to reach a velocity of 120 km/h straight up, assuming constant mass and thrust? (c) In reality, the mass of a rocket decreases significantly as its fuel is consumed. Describe qualitatively how this affects the acceleration and time for this motion.</para></problem></exercise><exercise id="fs-id3065143" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id3065145">
